An orienting example

library(gapminder)
data(gapminder)

Weâll just keep the most recent data in this dataset (2007).

gm2007 <- gapminder |> 
  filter(year == 2007)
ggplot(gm2007,
            aes(x = gdpPercap,
                y = lifeExp)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .2)

What is the correlation? Why might correlation not be the best number to work with here?

gm2007 |> 
  select(gdpPercap, lifeExp) |> 
  cor()
          gdpPercap   lifeExp
gdpPercap 1.0000000 0.6786624
lifeExp   0.6786624 1.0000000

What is correlation?

Letâs start with a few ideas.

mean

The mean is the most common measure of the âaverageâ value.

\[\bar{x} = \frac{\sum x_i}{n}\] Letâs check the mean value of life expectancy in these data.

mean(gm2007$lifeExp)
[1] 67.00742

standard deviation

The standard deviation is a measure of how spread out the data are.

\[SD_x = \sqrt{\frac{\sum (x_i - \bar{x})^2}{n-1}} \] First letâs look at this visually.

ggplot(gm2007,
       aes(x = lifeExp)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 2,
                 color = "white")

ASIDE: if youâre looking to get a good baseline for breaks, try this.

breaks <- pretty(
  gm2007$lifeExp,                   # give it the variable
  nclass.Sturges(gm2007$lifeExp))   # ask "Sturges" to tell you how many bins

breaks
 [1] 35 40 45 50 55 60 65 70 75 80 85
ggplot(gm2007,
       aes(x = lifeExp)) +
  geom_histogram(breaks = breaks,
                 color = "white") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = mean(gm2007$lifeExp),
             color = "red",
             linetype = "dashed")

What is the standard deviation here?

sd(gm2007$lifeExp)
[1] 12.07302

The âempiricalâ rule: if you canât visualize the data for some reason, itâs a reasonable approximation to estimate that 68% of the data lie within 1 SD of the mean and 95% lie within 2 SDs of the mean. This works better the more âbell shapedâ (i.e., ânormalâ) your data are. So it probably wouldnât work great here!

standardized variable

Variables are measured in units like dollars or years. If we want a âunitlessâ measure of something, we can standardize a variable. Letâs call that variable \(x^*\).

\[x^*_i = \frac{x_i-\bar{x}}{SD_x}\] The unit now is âhow many standard deviations from the mean is this observationâ?

correlation

To calculate the correlation between two variables, we need both variables standardized. Then apply this formula:

\[r_{xy} = \frac{\sum x^*_i y^*_i}{n} \] The idea here is when one variable is 1 standard deviation higher, the other variable will be \(r_{xy}\) standard deviations higher.

Letâs check this out.

# get means and SDs
mean_gdp <- mean(gm2007$gdpPercap)
sd_gdp <- sd(gm2007$gdpPercap)
mean_lexp <- mean(gm2007$lifeExp)
sd_lexp <- sd(gm2007$lifeExp)

# make new standardized variables
gm2007 <- gm2007 |> 
  mutate(z_gdp = (gdpPercap - mean_gdp) / sd_gdp,
         z_lexp = (lifeExp - mean_lexp) / sd_lexp)
ggplot(gm2007,
       aes(x = z_gdp,
           y = z_lexp)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .3) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0,
             linetype = "dashed",
             color = "red") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0,
             linetype = "dashed",
             color = "red")

Points in the bottom left and top right quadrants will increase the correlation value; points in the other quadrants will decrease it.

a note on the problem

Correlation is based on the idea of linear relationships. This relationship isnât very linear, perhaps due to the diminishing returns of the economy to life expectancy.

What if we used the base 2 log of GDP instead?

gm2007 <- gm2007 |> 
  mutate(log2gdp = log2(gdpPercap))
ggplot(gm2007,
       aes(x = log2gdp,
           y = lifeExp)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .3)

gm2007 <- gm2007 |> 
  mutate(log10gdp = log10(gdpPercap))
ggplot(gm2007,
       aes(x = log10gdp,
           y = lifeExp)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .3)

gm2007 |> 
  select(log2gdp,
         lifeExp) |> 
  cor()
          log2gdp   lifeExp
log2gdp 1.0000000 0.8089803
lifeExp 0.8089803 1.0000000

anscombe_long <- anscombe %>%
  pivot_longer(
    everything(),
    names_to = c(".value", "set"),
    names_pattern = "(.)(.)"

Now letâs compute the mean and SD for each set of X and Y.

anscombe_long |> 
  group_by(set) |> 
  summarize(
    across(.cols = c(x, y), 
           .fns = list(mean = mean, sd = sd), 
           .names = "{col}_{fn}"))
# A tibble: 4 Ã 5
  set   x_mean  x_sd y_mean  y_sd
  <chr>  <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl> <dbl>
1 1          9  3.32   7.50  2.03
2 2          9  3.32   7.50  2.03
3 3          9  3.32   7.5   2.03
4 4          9  3.32   7.50  2.03

They look the same, but these sorts of numbers can be deceiving!

Now letâs plot the scatter plots of each of the four sets.

ggplot(anscombe_long,
       aes(x = x,
           y = y)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .5) +
  facet_wrap(~set)

Without looking at the data, this would be very hard to notice!

A football (soccer) example

library(worldfootballR)
d <- fb_match_results(country = "ENG",
                      gender = "M",
                      season_end_year = 2022)

How well does xG track with actual goals?

Again, we donât want HomeGoals/AwayGoals and Home_xG and Away_xG in different columns. We donât care about game results here, so letâs get a structure where all the goals are in one column and all the xgs are in another.

d2 <- d |>
  mutate(matchid = 1:nrow(d)) |> 
  select(matchid, Home, Away, HomeGoals, AwayGoals, Home_xG, Away_xG) |>
  rename(team1 = Home,
         team2 = Away,
         xg1 = Home_xG,
         xg2 = Away_xG,
         goals1 = HomeGoals,
         goals2 = AwayGoals) |>
  pivot_longer(
    cols = c(-matchid),
    names_pattern = "(.+)([12])",
    names_to = c(".value", "home_away"),
    values_to = c("team", "goals", "xg"))

Whatâs the correlation between xG and goals?

cor(d2$goals,
    d2$xg)
[1] 0.6735144

Plot it!

ggplot(d2,
       aes(x = xg,
           y = goals)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = .3) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm",
              se = FALSE,
              linetype = "dashed")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
